# Firebase Realtime Database Patterns

## Data Modeling — Keep it Flat
Avoid deep nesting. Denormalize data to enable efficient queries.

```
// ❌ BAD — nested bookings under rooms
rooms/
  room1/
    bookings/
      booking1: { ... }

// ✅ GOOD — flat, cross-referenced
rooms/
  room1: { name, capacity }
bookings/
  booking1: { roomId, userId, startTime, endTime }
userBookings/
  userId1/
    booking1: true   ← index for fast user lookup
```

## Reading Data
- Use `.onValue` stream for real-time updates (live UI)
- Use `.get()` (once) for one-shot fetches (e.g., on submit)
- Always scope queries to the smallest node needed

```dart
// ✅ Stream for live room availability
final stream = _db.ref('rooms').onValue;

// ✅ One-shot for booking confirmation
final snapshot = await _db.ref('bookings/$id').get();
```

## Writing Data
- Use `set()` for new records with a known key
- Use `push()` to let Firebase generate unique keys
- Use `update()` for partial updates across multiple paths (atomic)

```dart
// ✅ Atomic multi-path write
await _db.ref().update({
  'bookings/$bookingId': bookingData,
  'userBookings/$userId/$bookingId': true,
});
```

## Performance
- Index queried fields in `firebase.json` security rules (`".indexOn"`)
- Avoid `limitToFirst` / `orderByChild` on large unindexed nodes
- Detach listeners (`cancel()` on stream subscription) when widgets dispose
